</div><br />
I think my last test shows pretty clearly that aggro doesn't decay. I'm repeating myself, but after building aggro with the cleric and taunting it off (did zero damage or any taunt-building stuff whatsoever with the warrior...taunt only, and I was ducking to avoid any damage from ripostes).  Then the cleric zoned out and back in to clear his aggro.  The warrior sat there tanking the mob while ducked and doing absolutely nothing to the mob for something like 7 minutes.  Then I attacked the mob with the cleric meleeing for a while...didn't get aggro.  Then I CH'd the tank....didn't get aggro.  To finally get aggro I had to cast stun on the mob something like 6 times in addition to the CH and the melee.  I think it's pretty clear that the aggro the tank got from taunting off of the cleric (the ONLY thing he did to get aggro) had not decayed in the 7 minutes since he got it.<br />
<br />
Your tank switching example is simplistic at best.  Taunt is only one of many factors in aggro when everyone is attacking and has been for a few minutes.</div>
