	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Brutal, <br />
I was farther away than Farlander in both tests, iirc.<br />
<br />
Distance does play a large role in agro, especially when you are a ranger PL'ing a chanter.  The chanter had to run through me quite often to ditch mobs on me, otherwise they'd stay agro'd on her regardless of how many snares I threw on them.<br />
<br />
In fact the whole PL'ing experience makes me believe that there is a difference between damage agro and non-damage agro.<br />
<br />
.... more random thoughts....<br />
Remember the spike agro issue that came in when they extended the hate list?  Well they fixed that, but that fix came after the testing I did and before the testing Brutal did.  I don't wonder if they broke something when they fixed that problem.<br />
<br />
<br />
Agro decay...  Brutal's test is not conclusive but definately a strong indicator that agro doesn't fade over time.  However there is some agro fade going on in xp groups.  Remember before horses and all outdoor zones?  Back then clerics were not supposed to heal and then instantly sit or they would pull agro.  I believe they had to wait a few seconds and then sit.  So there was some agro fading going on there.  In fact I still see that behavior nowadays if I nuke during the pull, and then sit right after losing agro to switch out spells.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
